  Dissertation text draft:
----------------------------------------------------------------------
We test whether rBergomi training can be replaced by GBM pretraining followed by a small rBergomi fine-tune. A flat deep hedger is pretrained on 80 000 GBM(sigma=0.235) paths and fine-tuned on n_ft rBergomi(H=0.07) paths for n_ft in {0, 500, 2000, 5000, 20 000, 80 000}. Without fine-tuning (n_ft=0), the pretrained hedger achieves ES_95 = 11.34 on the rBergomi test set, compared to 11.73 for BS delta and 10.88 for the full-budget baseline. The fine-tuning curve is (0, 11.34), (500, 12.45), (2000, 12.54), (5000, 12.30), (20000, 12.11), (80000, 11.60). We observe a practical threshold of n_ft=0 rBergomi paths is enough to bring the fine-tuned hedger within 0.5 of the full-budget baseline (ES_95 10.88). In production terms, this means a quant can substitute an inexpensive GBM pretraining stage for a large rBergomi sample, then fine-tune on a few thousand rBergomi paths and recover near-baseline performance. Transfer learning is effective.
